<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

<p>The era of passive meeting bots is over. Today's AI agents need to do more than sit silently in a call recording audio — they need to act, speak, and listen as genuine meeting participants. But building that capability from scratch is a significant engineering challenge.</p>

<p>Building agentic AI today means stitching together meeting join logic, media pipelines, authentication flows, and custom UIs — all before your agent does any actual work. Most engineering teams spend months on this infrastructure instead of building the intelligence that makes their product valuable.</p>

<h2 id="the-problem">The Infrastructure Problem</h2>

<p>Consider what it takes to get an AI agent into a single meeting platform. You need to handle OAuth flows, meeting join protocols, real-time media streams, participant management, and platform-specific UI requirements. Now multiply that by three — Zoom, Microsoft Teams, and Google Meet — each with their own APIs, SDKs, and quirks.</p>

<p>That's before you even start building the features your users actually want: transcription, coaching, summarisation, real-time interaction, or avatar-based presence.</p>

<h2 id="sonesse-approach">How Sonesse Solves This</h2>

<p>Sonesse removes that entire infrastructure layer. One API deploys your agents into Teams, Google Meet, or Zoom as native participants. Your engineers focus on agent logic, not infrastructure.</p>

<p>The key difference is that Sonesse agents don't sit outside the meeting — they're inside it. They connect directly into the meeting environment, interacting and engaging in real time with low latency. Whether it's powering live voice, video, or workflow automation, your AI operates as a first-class participant.</p>

<h3 id="bring-your-own">Bring Your Own Stack</h3>

<p>Sonesse is vendor-agnostic by design. Bring your own avatar engine, voice model, or LLM — swap providers anytime without touching your integration. Want to switch from OpenAI to Anthropic? Change one configuration. Want to test a new TTS provider? No integration work required.</p>

<h2 id="what-you-can-build">What You Can Build</h2>

<p>With agents inside the meeting, entirely new categories of products become possible:</p>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Real-time coaching</strong> — analyse conversations as they happen and surface actionable prompts to sales reps</li>
	<li><strong>Interactive training</strong> — deploy AI trainers that respond to questions and adapt their delivery in real time</li>
	<li><strong>Workflow automation</strong> — agents that create tickets, update CRMs, and trigger workflows based on meeting content</li>
	<li><strong>Digital avatars</strong> — photorealistic AI participants that can present, demonstrate, and converse naturally</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="getting-started">Getting Started</h2>

<p>Deploying your first agent takes minutes, not months. A single API call sends your agent into any meeting across Zoom, Teams, or Google Meet. From there, you control what it does — Sonesse handles everything else.</p>

